    <name>
				<text>16.2.5.2 Ratio test convergence</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Use the ratio test alone to examine the convergence of the series:</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>\(\displaystyle \sum_{p=1}^\infty \frac{e^{@a1@}}{(2p+1)^{p+1}}\). The ratio test is [[input:ans1]].[[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</li>
    <li>\(\displaystyle \sum_{p=1}^\infty \frac{p^{@a2@}}{p!}\). The ratio test is [[input:ans2]]. [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</li>
    <li>\(\displaystyle \sum_{p=1}^\infty \frac{1}{\sqrt{p}}\). The ratio test is [[input:ans3]]. [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</li>
    <li>\(\displaystyle \sum_{p=1}^\infty \frac{1}{({@a3@})^p}\). The ratio test is [[input:ans4]]. [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</li>
    <li>\(\displaystyle \sum_{p=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{p+1}}{{@a4@}^p}\). The ratio test is [[input:ans5]]. [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>
        <p>The general term of this series is \(\displaystyle a_p = \frac{e^{@a1@}}{(2p + 1)^{p+1}}\). Then</p>
        \[\begin{aligned} \lambda = \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{a_{p+1}}{a_p} &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{e^{@a1@}}{(2(p+1) + 1)^{p+2}} \cdot \frac{(2p + 1)^{p+1}}{e^{@a1@}} \\ &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{(2p + 1)^{p+1}}{(2(p+1) + 1)^{p+2}} \\ &amp;=
        \lim_{p \to \infty} \left(\frac{2p + 1}{2p + 3}\right)^{p+1} \cdot \frac{1}{2p + 3} \\ &amp;\leq 1 \cdot \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{1}{2p + 3} \\ &amp;= 1 \cdot 0 = 0. \end{aligned}\]
        <p>But the limit is clearly nonnegative, so we conclude that \(\lambda = 0\). Since \(\lambda &lt; 1\), the series <b>converves</b>.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>The general term of this series is \(\displaystyle a_p = \frac{p^{@a2@}}{p!}\). Then</p>
        \[\begin{aligned} \lambda = \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{a_{p+1}}{a_p} &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{(p+1)^{@a2@}}{(p+1)!} \cdot \frac{p!}{p^{@a2@}} \\ &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \left(\frac{p+1}{p}\right)^{@a2@} \cdot \frac{1}{p+1} \\ &amp;= 1 \cdot
        0 = 0. \end{aligned}\]
        <p>Since \(\lambda &lt; 1\), the series <b>converges</b>.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>The general term of this series is \(\displaystyle a_p = \frac{1}{\sqrt{p}}\). Then</p>
        \[\begin{aligned} \lambda = \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{a_{p+1}}{a_p} &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{1}{\sqrt{p+1}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{p}}{1} \\ &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{\sqrt{p}}{\sqrt{p+1}} \\ &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \sqrt{\frac{p}{p+1}} \\
        &amp;= 1. \end{aligned}\]
        <p>Since \(\lambda = 1\), the ratio test is <b>inconclusive</b>. Nevertheless, note that \(\displaystyle \frac{1}{\sqrt{p}} &gt; \frac{1}{p}\) for all \(p\), so our series diverges by comparison with the harmonic series.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>The general term of this series is \(\displaystyle a_p = \frac{1}{({@a3@})^p}\). Then</p>
        \[\begin{aligned} \lambda = \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{a_{p+1}}{a_p} &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{1}{({@a3@})^{p+1}} \cdot \frac{({@a3@})^p}{1} \\ &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{({@a3@})^{p}}{({@a3@})^{p+1}} \\ &amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{1}{{@a3@}}
        \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{{@a3@}} \approx {@decimalplaces(1/a3,3)@}. \end{aligned}\]
        <p>Since \(\lambda &gt; 1\), the series <b>diverges</b>.</p>
    </li>
  <li><p>The general term of this series is \(\displaystyle a_p = \frac{(-1)^{p+1}}{{@a4@}^p}\). Note that this is not always positive, so we cannot apply the ratio test. It is thus <b>inconclusive</b>. Nevertheless, this series is absolutely convergent, and thus convergent.</p></li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
